"Ah, he's an old guy

00:26.610 --> 00:28.528
and he's a flake.
All right, he's not a problem."

00:28.528 --> 00:31.198
But, who knows, you know?
It's an adventure.

00:31.198 --> 00:34.284
- My name is Aaron Morrison.
I'm 19 years old.

00:34.284 --> 00:36.119
I'm from Hickory,
North Carolina.

00:36.119 --> 00:37.871
<i>I started bladesmithing</i>
<i>because what's cooler</i>

00:37.871 --> 00:40.916
than putting metal
into a raging fire

00:40.916 --> 00:42.709
<i>that's over 2000 degrees?</i>

00:42.709 --> 00:45.837
It's old school and old school
is cool school, man.

00:45.837 --> 00:47.214
<i>- My name is</i>
<i>John Grady Hippard.</i>

00:47.214 --> 00:49.007
<i>I'm from Corsicana, Texas.</i>

00:49.007 --> 00:51.635
By trade,
I am a combination pipe welder.

00:51.635 --> 00:54.680
Each knife I make has
its own personality.

00:54.680 --> 00:57.015
<i>When I hand</i>
<i>a customer a knife...</i>

00:57.015 --> 01:00.143
it brings me
all the joy in the world.

01:00.143 --> 01:03.772
<i>My name is JC Cruzan.</i>
<i>I'm 31 years old.</i>

01:03.772 --> 01:05.065
I currently work
in a high security facility

01:05.065 --> 01:06.692
in the state of New Hampshire

01:06.692 --> 01:08.944
<i>for juveniles</i>
<i>who commit adult crimes.</i>

01:08.944 --> 01:12.030
It's a high stress environment
because at any moment

01:12.030 --> 01:14.241
<i>you could have a situation</i>
<i>that gets violent.</i>

01:14.241 --> 01:17.911
So bladesmithing to me
is my form of therapy.

01:17.911 --> 01:20.622
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:20.622 --> 01:22.958
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:22.958 --> 01:24.501
You are here
to engage in three rounds

01:24.501 --> 01:26.169
of edged-weapon-making
competition

01:26.169 --> 01:28.714
like nothing you've ever
experienced before

01:28.714 --> 01:31.508
in the hopes of becoming our
next "Forged in Fire" champion,

01:31.508 --> 01:34.094
who also leaves here
with a check for $10,000.

01:34.094 --> 01:38.515
We're gonna test you mentally,
creatively, and physically

01:38.515 --> 01:40.350
in front of a panel
of expert judges,

01:40.350 --> 01:42.019
so let's meet them now.

01:42.019 --> 01:45.105
Up first, ABS Master smith,
J. Neilson.

01:45.105 --> 01:47.232
Next, Historic Weapons
Re-creation Specialist,

01:47.232 --> 01:48.900
David Baker.

01:48.900 --> 01:50.736
And last,
Edged Weapons Specialist,

01:50.736 --> 01:53.739
Doug Marcaida.

01:53.739 --> 01:55.282
All right, gents,
we all know that

01:55.282 --> 01:56.992
when you're forging a blade
a nice,

01:56.992 --> 01:59.286
rectangular piece of steel
is a good place to start

01:59.286 --> 02:01.830
but we'd like to make it
more challenging.

02:01.830 --> 02:05.000
So, instead, you'll be choosing
the steel that you use today

02:05.000 --> 02:07.794
from this burning barrel.

02:07.794 --> 02:10.881
So in an order randomly chosen,
each of you will pick the steel

02:10.881 --> 02:13.091
that you're going to use
from the barrel.

02:13.091 --> 02:15.719
John, you're up first.
Please choose your steel.

02:15.719 --> 02:17.512
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:17.512 --> 02:19.222
<i>- I hope and pray that</i>

02:19.222 --> 02:20.932
<i>I'm gonna get something</i>
<i>easy to work with.</i>

02:20.932 --> 02:23.060
Whatever I choose,
I hope I'm familiar with it.

02:23.060 --> 02:26.146
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:26.146 --> 02:28.774
- Those are cubes of 1095.

02:28.774 --> 02:31.485
- I was excited
that it was 1095.

02:31.485 --> 02:35.155
<i>I was not excited that it was</i>
<i>cubes shaped like a pyramid.</i>

02:35.155 --> 02:37.491
<i>It's gonna be a challenge</i>
<i>on how to use</i>

02:37.491 --> 02:40.077
all the cubes
or just one cube.

02:40.077 --> 02:42.162
- Matt, you're up next.
Choose your steel.

02:42.162 --> 02:45.999
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:45.999 --> 02:49.670
An elegant fan
of 5160 spring steel.

02:49.670 --> 02:52.547
- 5160 is
a deep hardening steel.

02:52.547 --> 02:53.757
<i>It's got chromium in it.</i>

02:53.757 --> 02:55.217
<i>I've never worked with a steel</i>

02:55.217 --> 02:57.260
<i>that had any chromium in it.</i>

02:57.260 --> 02:59.262
I'm not sure
how it's going to behave,

02:59.262 --> 03:01.556
how it's going to weld.

03:01.556 --> 03:03.725
- JC, you're up next.

03:03.725 --> 03:08.647
- Seeing these guys pick out
these cubes of steel and fans,

03:08.647 --> 03:11.149
I'm definitely nervous.

03:11.149 --> 03:13.318
- Discs of W2.

03:13.318 --> 03:16.238
- I get a [bleep]
lollipop of W2.

03:16.238 --> 03:19.157
<i>I've never ever</i>
<i>worked with W2 before.</i>

03:19.157 --> 03:20.951
- All right, Aaron, you're up.

03:20.951 --> 03:24.037
- Oh, crap.
What is in store for me?

03:24.037 --> 03:26.873
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:26.873 --> 03:29.918
- You got four fingers
of 1084 round stock.

03:29.918 --> 03:32.045
- This weird shape.

03:32.045 --> 03:33.797
It looked like maybe a trident,
but it had four...

03:33.797 --> 03:35.924
[laughs]
So maybe a quadrant.

03:35.924 --> 03:38.885
- Your first round challenge
is to forge...

03:38.885 --> 03:40.512
a hatchet.

03:40.512 --> 03:42.347
- And my stomach
does the splits.

03:42.347 --> 03:44.558
<i>I've made</i>
<i>a few hatchets at home</i>

03:44.558 --> 03:47.727
but this is a whole
different world than home.

03:47.727 --> 03:51.022
- Your hatchets must be
<i>between 6 and 8 inches</i>

03:51.022 --> 03:52.983
<i>from butt to edge</i>

03:52.983 --> 03:56.194
<i>and your edge must be</i>
<i>between 4 and 6 inches.</i>

03:56.194 --> 03:58.822
Make sure you stick
to those parameters.

03:58.822 --> 04:00.574
Keep in mind
that in the second round

04:00.574 --> 04:02.242
you'll be attaching handles
to those blades

04:02.242 --> 04:05.704
turning them into
fully functional weapons.

04:05.704 --> 04:08.540
Your weapons will be tested
for strength and durability

04:08.540 --> 04:10.834
in a railroad tie chop

04:10.834 --> 04:14.296
and for edge retention
in a leather bag slice.

04:14.296 --> 04:16.339
You will have
three hours in this round.

04:16.339 --> 04:17.841
When the time runs out

04:17.841 --> 04:19.342
and your blades
have been inspected,

04:19.342 --> 04:21.011
one of you will have
to surrender your hatchet

04:21.011 --> 04:22.512
and leave this forge.

04:22.512 --> 04:24.264
Good luck, bladesmiths.

04:24.264 --> 04:25.849
Your three hours starts...
now.

04:25.849 --> 04:28.685
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:28.685 --> 04:30.562
We've got four
different types of steel

04:30.562 --> 04:32.564
and four
different configurations.

04:32.564 --> 04:34.274
What's the first thing
you're doing, J.?

04:34.274 --> 04:35.525
- First thing
I'm gonna be doing is

04:35.525 --> 04:37.277
breaking those pieces apart

04:37.277 --> 04:39.154
and cleaning
the welding bead off of them

04:39.154 --> 04:40.614
so it doesn't interfere
with my forge welding.

04:40.614 --> 04:42.866
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:42.866 --> 04:45.535
<i>- Wil says go</i>
<i>and my first thought is,</i>

04:45.535 --> 04:47.454
"Crap, I don't know
how to make an axe."

04:47.454 --> 04:51.249
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:51.249 --> 04:52.918
- Matt--
- Matt's tearing it up.

04:52.918 --> 04:56.129
- I picked up
a bunch of strips of 5160

04:56.129 --> 04:57.881
which is great 'cause
they're flat and rectangular

04:57.881 --> 05:00.342
but I have to clean
all the surfaces.

05:00.342 --> 05:02.552
The critical part's coming up.

05:02.552 --> 05:05.889
I gotta stick these
all together and ugh.

05:05.889 --> 05:08.266
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:08.266 --> 05:10.143
- Let's talk a little bit
about hatchets.

05:10.143 --> 05:12.687
Hatchets come in all kinds
of sizes and shapes.

05:12.687 --> 05:15.148
- When you're talking about
axes, they're small axes.

05:15.148 --> 05:16.733
Some people think hatchets
are these bigger things

05:16.733 --> 05:18.109
that are bigger than hands
and go--

05:18.109 --> 05:21.071
if the balance and feel
is too heavy

05:21.071 --> 05:22.614
it's not a hatchet.

05:22.614 --> 05:24.199
<i>- Immediately I'm thinking,</i>

05:24.199 --> 05:27.369
<i>"Okay, go ahead</i>
<i>and cut everything off,</i>

05:27.369 --> 05:30.789
flatten it out and then we'll
stack it and weld it."

05:30.789 --> 05:32.415
- It's nice to see our smiths

05:32.415 --> 05:34.751
clean up each and every one
of their metals.

05:34.751 --> 05:36.545
- All right,
time to get them hot.

05:36.545 --> 05:38.755
Gonna throw them in the forge.

05:38.755 --> 05:40.799
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:40.799 --> 05:44.010
<i>- My first step</i>
<i>is to isolate a single cube</i>

05:44.010 --> 05:45.595
<i>and then I'll take it</i>
<i>to the grinder,</i>

05:45.595 --> 05:47.764
<i>start cleaning it up.</i>

05:47.764 --> 05:50.475
<i>I think one of those</i>
<i>little bitty cubes</i>

05:50.475 --> 05:53.103
<i>is gonna be</i>
<i>enough steel for a bit.</i>

05:53.103 --> 05:56.690
The high carbon bit is
gonna go where the edge will.

05:56.690 --> 05:58.692
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:58.692 --> 06:02.904
<i>I'm gonna grab</i>
<i>a rectangle of mild steel.</i>

06:02.904 --> 06:05.991
<i>I'll draw out the mild steel</i>
<i>to form the jacket</i>

06:05.991 --> 06:07.784
<i>and then insert the bit</i>

06:07.784 --> 06:10.537
<i>and it's just a simple</i>
<i>forge weld from there.</i>

06:10.537 --> 06:15.542
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:15.542 --> 06:19.087
- The first thing I want to do
is get these discs apart.

06:19.087 --> 06:21.756
Mother[bleep]

06:21.756 --> 06:24.301
The grinder's not cutting
through the welds

06:24.301 --> 06:25.552
the way I want them to.

06:25.552 --> 06:27.929
<i>Time to try something new.</i>

06:27.929 --> 06:30.807
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.

06:30.807 --> 06:32.767
That's what I wanted.

06:32.767 --> 06:35.478
<i>My next step is</i>
<i>to clean up the surfaces</i>

06:35.478 --> 06:38.023
because nothing's gonna
forge weld together

06:38.023 --> 06:40.191
with dirty surfaces.

06:40.191 --> 06:42.319
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:42.319 --> 06:43.904
- Attack 'em and stack 'em.

06:43.904 --> 06:45.822
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:45.822 --> 06:48.617
<i>I made sure</i>
<i>to have a very strong weld</i>

06:48.617 --> 06:50.243
<i>that way</i>
<i>they won't come apart</i>

06:50.243 --> 06:51.244
while I'm trying
to forge weld.

06:51.244 --> 06:52.912
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:52.912 --> 06:54.456
<i>It's a big, ol' CandyVille.</i>

06:54.456 --> 06:57.125
<i>You just gotta</i>
<i>go happy with it.</i>

06:57.125 --> 06:59.252
I use flux very generously.

06:59.252 --> 07:00.587
Do another fluxin'.

07:00.587 --> 07:03.340
Fluxin' for the lovin'.

07:03.340 --> 07:06.176
You gotta give it
like it's sugar to a baby.

07:06.176 --> 07:09.262
Gotta season it.
Like seasoning a steak.

07:09.262 --> 07:12.015
<i>The more, the better, because</i>
<i>if we can prevent oxygen</i>

07:12.015 --> 07:14.100
from getting into
those different layers

07:14.100 --> 07:16.019
the better forge weld
we're gonna have.

07:16.019 --> 07:19.147
- Aaron setting weld.

07:19.147 --> 07:20.982
- Aaron's steel sounds good.

07:20.982 --> 07:22.442
Sounds solid.

07:22.442 --> 07:25.070
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:25.070 --> 07:26.529
- It's not sugar.
Don't eat it.

07:26.529 --> 07:28.323
- What?
- It's not sugar.

07:28.323 --> 07:29.949
Don't eat it.

07:29.949 --> 07:31.201
- Aaron's talking to me
the whole time

07:31.201 --> 07:32.619
and, to tell you the truth,

07:32.619 --> 07:33.912
I can't hear
a damn thing he's saying.

07:33.912 --> 07:36.790
- Put that borax
like it's sugar.

07:36.790 --> 07:38.625
- Yeah.
- Tons of it.

07:38.625 --> 07:40.335
- I'm just smiling
and nodding my head and saying,

07:40.335 --> 07:41.670
"Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah."

07:41.670 --> 07:45.590
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:45.590 --> 07:47.133
- Matt moving right along.

07:47.133 --> 07:49.386
His billet looks beautiful.

07:49.386 --> 07:51.304
- The welds look like
they stack perfectly

07:51.304 --> 07:54.182
so I am totally pumped.

07:54.182 --> 07:56.059
- One hour has elapsed.

07:56.059 --> 07:59.396
That leaves you two hours
remaining to finish your work.

07:59.396 --> 08:02.399
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:02.399 --> 08:05.276
- John has a massive chunk

08:05.276 --> 08:08.405
of mild steel over at big blue.

08:08.405 --> 08:10.031
- Yeah, John's probably
gonna end up

08:10.031 --> 08:12.992
with more steel for his body
than he's gonna need.

08:12.992 --> 08:14.994
- At first,
it's going pretty well.

08:14.994 --> 08:18.331
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:18.331 --> 08:20.959
Oh, that's ugly.

08:20.959 --> 08:22.544
Ugh.

08:22.544 --> 08:24.462
Gotta start over.

08:24.462 --> 08:27.006
Things weren't
lining up very well, I...

08:27.006 --> 08:29.384
started off with too much metal
and then I took some off.

08:29.384 --> 08:30.885
It was still too much.

08:30.885 --> 08:32.846
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:32.846 --> 08:35.056
<i>So I just cut my losses</i>
<i>as quickly as I could</i>

08:35.056 --> 08:38.017
and started on another piece.

08:38.017 --> 08:40.019
<i>The first one was too big.</i>

08:40.019 --> 08:43.022
<i>This smaller jacket is going</i>
<i>a whole lot better</i>

08:43.022 --> 08:46.693
but the clock is starting
to catch up with me.

08:46.693 --> 08:49.112
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:49.112 --> 08:51.990
<i>- The clock is moving</i>
<i>a lot faster than I expected.</i>

08:51.990 --> 08:55.660
<i>I grab all my biscuits of W2,</i>
<i>clamp it together,</i>

08:55.660 --> 08:58.079
<i>and I weld as tight</i>
<i>as I possibly can.</i>

08:58.079 --> 08:59.831
- JC just put steel
in the fire.

08:59.831 --> 09:02.250
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:02.250 --> 09:05.837
- Looks like JC's stack
is sliding over.

09:05.837 --> 09:07.464
Kind of like
a melting wedding cake.

09:07.464 --> 09:08.798
- Ah.

09:08.798 --> 09:10.884
Is that a seam in the middle?

09:10.884 --> 09:13.428
- I'm realizing that
the steel is still kind of--

09:13.428 --> 09:16.139
like there's spaces
and gaps in between.

09:16.139 --> 09:17.474
Yep, there we go.

09:17.474 --> 09:19.100
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:19.100 --> 09:22.395
<i>It's not forge welding.</i>
<i>[bleep].</i>

09:22.395 --> 09:24.230
- I'm very worried
about JC right now.

09:24.230 --> 09:25.774
<i>- The steel that</i>
<i>I have right now,</i>

09:25.774 --> 09:27.025
<i>it's just loaded</i>
<i>with forge scale.</i>

09:27.025 --> 09:28.693
<i>If I pull it apart</i>

09:28.693 --> 09:30.612
<i>and start to grind it</i>
<i>and clean it up,</i>

09:30.612 --> 09:32.238
<i>it's just gonna take</i>
<i>even more time off the clock.</i>

09:32.238 --> 09:35.617
Instead of chasing the issue,
I scrap it.

09:35.617 --> 09:37.702
- I think JC's
actually starting over.

09:37.702 --> 09:39.662
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:39.662 --> 09:42.749
- Have to clean them
all up again.

09:42.749 --> 09:44.000
- Let's talk
a little bit about

09:44.000 --> 09:46.127
some of the features
of a hatchet.

09:46.127 --> 09:48.838
You're gonna have to find
a way to attach that head

09:48.838 --> 09:50.673
to the hatchet.
- Yep.

09:50.673 --> 09:52.801
How do you create the hole

09:52.801 --> 09:54.594
in the billet
to be able to do that?

09:54.594 --> 09:56.012
- Well,
the two main ways are

09:56.012 --> 09:57.806
drifting a hole through it...
- Right.

09:57.806 --> 10:00.016
- Or wrapping steel
around a form...

10:00.016 --> 10:01.684
- Okay.
- To make an eye for the shaft.

10:01.684 --> 10:03.978
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:03.978 --> 10:06.940
- Aaron.
He's got one solid billet

10:06.940 --> 10:09.150
drawn out and now looks like
he's gonna do the wrap.

10:09.150 --> 10:11.319
- Folding it creates the eye

10:11.319 --> 10:13.071
<i>that way I can then</i>
<i>forge weld the bits together</i>

10:13.071 --> 10:14.614
and as long as they're clean,

10:14.614 --> 10:16.324
we have a solid hatchet
to work with.

10:16.324 --> 10:18.284
That looks good.

10:18.284 --> 10:20.745
I think I have a chance
about beating my competitors.

10:20.745 --> 10:22.288
[burps, exhales]

10:22.288 --> 10:25.542
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:25.542 --> 10:28.586
- I'm drawing out
my billet on big blue

10:28.586 --> 10:31.381
<i>and I wanna even it up</i>
<i>a little more and spread it.</i>

10:31.381 --> 10:36.845
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:36.845 --> 10:38.721
[bleep].

10:38.721 --> 10:41.015
And the welds pop.

10:41.015 --> 10:42.684
- Oh, no.
His welds didn't hold.

10:42.684 --> 10:44.310
He's gonna be in big trouble.

10:44.310 --> 10:46.104
- I know I might look like

10:46.104 --> 10:48.189
I'm really focused,
cool, calm, and collected,

10:48.189 --> 10:49.941
but on the inside
I'm just going,

10:49.941 --> 10:51.234
"Oh, my God. Oh, my God.

10:51.234 --> 10:52.277
"What am I doing?
What am I doing?

10:52.277 --> 10:54.070
What am I gonna do now, wah!"

10:54.070 --> 10:56.156
- Man, this is not good.

10:56.156 --> 10:57.740
- He must have hit it
too hard on big blue.

10:57.740 --> 10:59.325
- This is a hatchet.

10:59.325 --> 11:01.494
You're gonna hit things
hard with it

11:01.494 --> 11:04.164
<i>and having those delaminations</i>

11:04.164 --> 11:07.375
is gonna allow stress
to just split the hatchet open.

11:07.375 --> 11:09.419
<i>I'm worried that</i>
<i>there's no recovery from this.</i>

11:11.629 --> 11:13.256
<i>[whooshing]</i>

11:13.256 --> 11:14.674
<i>I'm trying to get it</i>
<i>to the shape I want,</i>

11:14.674 --> 11:16.801
and the welds pop.

11:16.801 --> 11:18.720
- Oh, no.
His welds didn't hold.

11:18.720 --> 11:21.723
He's gonna be in big trouble.

11:21.723 --> 11:25.727
- How am I gonna go forward
with these delaminations.

11:25.727 --> 11:28.396
<i>I don't have enough material</i>
<i>to start over again.</i>

11:28.396 --> 11:30.815
I don't have time to fix this.

11:30.815 --> 11:33.526
<i>So my plan going forward is</i>

11:33.526 --> 11:35.278
to take the worst
of the delaminations,

11:35.278 --> 11:36.779
and get rid of them.

11:36.779 --> 11:38.948
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

11:38.948 --> 11:42.035
The first 1/3rd of it has
horrible delaminations in it.

11:42.035 --> 11:44.120
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:44.120 --> 11:46.539
So I go over to the chop saw
and just cut the bad part off.

11:46.539 --> 11:48.458
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:48.458 --> 11:51.211
<i>I'm feeling okay because</i>
<i>I can see the cut edges</i>

11:51.211 --> 11:53.296
and there aren't
any delams in it

11:53.296 --> 11:56.966
and the edge of the axe
is the most important.

11:56.966 --> 11:59.177
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:59.177 --> 12:01.512
- It looks like JC
is making a comeback.

12:01.512 --> 12:03.598
- I'm just hoping to get

12:03.598 --> 12:05.975
a nice, hard core
inside of a soft jacket.

12:05.975 --> 12:08.686
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:08.686 --> 12:11.189
I get a nice, good squish.
I feel like my welds are set.

12:11.189 --> 12:13.191
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:13.191 --> 12:14.609
Son of a [bleep].

12:14.609 --> 12:16.110
And I see it move.

12:16.110 --> 12:19.072
Ain't a whole left.
Ain't sticking.

12:19.072 --> 12:20.865
Third time's a charm.
- Uh-oh.

12:20.865 --> 12:22.617
- Oh, geez.
- The welds didn't take.

12:22.617 --> 12:24.285
- I think JC is actually
starting over.

12:24.285 --> 12:26.204
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:26.204 --> 12:29.082
<i>- My mild steel jacket</i>
<i>wasn't sticking</i>

12:29.082 --> 12:31.668
'cause I wasn't cleaning
my materials correctly.

12:31.668 --> 12:34.379
- JC is nervous
about time crunch.

12:34.379 --> 12:36.047
- W2 it is.

12:36.047 --> 12:38.341
So I scrap that

12:38.341 --> 12:42.178
and for the third try
I just use the W2.

12:42.178 --> 12:43.763
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:43.763 --> 12:45.556
All I know is
I got an hour left

12:45.556 --> 12:47.892
and I don't have anything
that looks like a hatchet.

12:47.892 --> 12:50.520
- Two hours has elapsed.

12:50.520 --> 12:53.273
You have just
60 minutes remaining.

12:53.273 --> 12:57.026
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:57.026 --> 12:58.278
- John's setting his welds.

12:58.278 --> 12:59.904
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:59.904 --> 13:02.031
<i>- It was difficult</i>
<i>starting over</i>

13:02.031 --> 13:04.993
but so far, things
are going a lot smoother

13:04.993 --> 13:06.995
then, um, the first time.

13:06.995 --> 13:10.248
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:10.248 --> 13:12.375
<i>Big blue takes me for a ride</i>

13:12.375 --> 13:14.168
and I'm just
all over the place with it.

13:14.168 --> 13:16.421
- John's ending up
with a really, really

13:16.421 --> 13:17.839
thin hatchet here.

13:17.839 --> 13:19.090
- Yay.

13:19.090 --> 13:20.633
<i>[tense music]</i>

13:20.633 --> 13:22.760
Pancake.

13:22.760 --> 13:25.013
I didn't get enough steel
to start with I don't think

13:25.013 --> 13:27.140
and that's why
I'm pretty thin.

13:27.140 --> 13:29.183
Big blue ate my lunch.

13:29.183 --> 13:31.811
<i>[tense drone]</i>

13:31.811 --> 13:37.191
- Aaron--his edge looks short
of the 4- to 6-inch range.

13:37.191 --> 13:39.402
- I want to be sure
that it's the right length.

13:39.402 --> 13:43.322
Whether it be from toe to heel,
or from butt to the bit.

13:43.322 --> 13:45.616
<i>And so I'm constantly</i>
<i>measuring it.</i>

13:45.616 --> 13:48.911
I got it to the dimension
that I want.

13:48.911 --> 13:51.289
- Aaron looks like he's about
ready to start quenching.

13:51.289 --> 13:54.792
<i>[tense music]</i>

13:54.792 --> 13:56.210
Pull the hatchet
out of the oil

13:56.210 --> 13:58.046
and everything
seems to be peachy.

13:58.046 --> 14:01.507
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

14:01.507 --> 14:04.135
- That isn't 4 inches.

14:04.135 --> 14:07.472
I think he has forgotten
what the parameters are.

14:07.472 --> 14:09.474
<i>- I'm pretty confident</i>
<i>with my hatchet.</i>

14:09.474 --> 14:12.101
I think I definitely have
a chance going to the second--

14:12.101 --> 14:14.103
maybe even the third round,
who knows?

14:14.103 --> 14:16.481
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:16.481 --> 14:18.733
- At this point
all I want to do

14:18.733 --> 14:20.568
is hand in something
for the judges to look at.

14:20.568 --> 14:22.779
It ain't over.

14:22.779 --> 14:25.698
I can probably still make
a hatchet out of this billet,

14:25.698 --> 14:27.533
I just don't know
how I'm going to forge it,

14:27.533 --> 14:28.868
'cause I've never forged
this shape before.

14:28.868 --> 14:30.328
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:30.328 --> 14:32.830
I have a eureka moment.

14:32.830 --> 14:36.167
I'm gonna go caveman on this.

14:36.167 --> 14:38.544
All I need to do is
use the drift as my guide

14:38.544 --> 14:40.046
and fold it over
on itself

14:40.046 --> 14:42.006
and forge weld
the W2 to the W2.

14:42.006 --> 14:44.342
Oh, yeah.
Getting there.

14:44.342 --> 14:45.802
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:45.802 --> 14:47.345
Are you serious?

14:47.345 --> 14:49.347
- As of right now,

14:49.347 --> 14:51.599
I think we've got two axes
that are short for parameter.

14:51.599 --> 14:53.643
- I didn't forge it
out thick enough.

14:53.643 --> 14:56.145
- You have 15 minutes remaining
in this round.

14:56.145 --> 14:58.439
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:58.439 --> 15:01.067
- JC is just fighting.

15:01.067 --> 15:03.694
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:03.694 --> 15:07.115
- We've seen miracles happen
here in this forge in less time

15:07.115 --> 15:09.867
so he's definitely not
out of the game yet.

15:09.867 --> 15:11.619
- At this point
all I'm trying to do

15:11.619 --> 15:13.746
is chase the width.

15:13.746 --> 15:15.706
I need 4 inches.

15:15.706 --> 15:18.835
Parameters aren't right,
I don't move on.

15:18.835 --> 15:21.838
<i>[intense music]</i>

15:21.838 --> 15:23.673
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:23.673 --> 15:26.050
- My eye is kinda
giving me a little trouble

15:26.050 --> 15:27.552
<i>because it's very small.</i>

15:27.552 --> 15:29.595
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:29.595 --> 15:31.139
- It looks like
John's trying to round out

15:31.139 --> 15:32.682
the eye of his hatchet
with the drift.

15:32.682 --> 15:33.891
He's gotta be able
to fit a handle in there

15:33.891 --> 15:35.351
in the second round.

15:35.351 --> 15:37.145
- Not exactly
the way I'd be doing it.

15:37.145 --> 15:39.063
- No.

15:39.063 --> 15:42.441
<i>- It's gonna be a small eye,</i>
<i>but it will do.</i>

15:42.441 --> 15:44.485
[whirring]

15:44.485 --> 15:51.159
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:51.159 --> 15:52.702
- John's hatchet head
is very thin

15:52.702 --> 15:54.453
from the eye to the edge.

15:54.453 --> 15:57.165
We know it's all mild steel
and he just edge quenched.

15:57.165 --> 15:58.791
is that gonna be an issue?

15:58.791 --> 16:00.626
- No, it should be fine
as long as he's got

16:00.626 --> 16:02.753
that hardenable steel
all the way around the edge.

16:02.753 --> 16:06.007
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:06.007 --> 16:07.758
- Matt just
quenched his blade.

16:07.758 --> 16:09.427
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:09.427 --> 16:11.762
- I think I'm good.

16:11.762 --> 16:14.765
- Ten, nine, eight,

16:14.765 --> 16:17.935
seven, six, five,

16:17.935 --> 16:19.937
four, three,

16:19.937 --> 16:21.939
two, one.

16:21.939 --> 16:23.482
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

16:23.482 --> 16:24.734
Drop your tools.

16:24.734 --> 16:26.903
This round is over.

16:26.903 --> 16:29.113
[clapping]
- Whoo!

16:29.113 --> 16:30.656
<i>- I'm just really proud</i>
<i>that I was able</i>

16:30.656 --> 16:32.700
to build something
in the three hours.

16:32.700 --> 16:36.245
The judges are just gonna
have to decide for themselves.

16:36.245 --> 16:37.955
- All right, bladesmiths,

16:37.955 --> 16:39.749
in this first round
of competition

16:39.749 --> 16:41.459
you were to make hatchets.

16:41.459 --> 16:43.085
Now it's time
for the judges

16:43.085 --> 16:45.046
to take a closer look
at your work.

16:45.046 --> 16:46.714
Matt, you're up first.

16:46.714 --> 16:50.092
Please present your hatchet
to the judges.

16:50.092 --> 16:53.387
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:53.387 --> 16:56.599
- I like that you got
the little clip beard on here.

16:56.599 --> 16:58.267
Definitely have to do
something about this

16:58.267 --> 16:59.477
because you're off center.

16:59.477 --> 17:01.312
But overall, nicely done.

17:01.312 --> 17:03.147
- Thank you.

17:03.147 --> 17:05.066
- Aaron, young man,
you're up next.

17:05.066 --> 17:09.987
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:09.987 --> 17:12.240
- There is a lot of meat here.

17:12.240 --> 17:15.159
That's gonna be
a lot of weight on the shaft.

17:15.159 --> 17:17.495
Your alignment isn't bad

17:17.495 --> 17:19.789
but you got a bow
right in here.

17:19.789 --> 17:22.583
I'm a little worried about
how long your edge is here.

17:22.583 --> 17:23.960
- Yes, sir.

17:23.960 --> 17:25.670
- It was fun
to watch you out there,

17:25.670 --> 17:29.006
you're very patient with
the work that you were doing.

17:29.006 --> 17:30.258
The metal looks good.

17:30.258 --> 17:32.343
Don't see any cracks.

17:32.343 --> 17:33.719
- Thank you, sir.

17:33.719 --> 17:35.263
- All right, John,
you're up.

17:35.263 --> 17:38.140
Please present
your blade to the judges.

17:38.140 --> 17:41.769
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:41.769 --> 17:43.229
- Yeah, that's lean.

17:43.229 --> 17:44.939
Shape is really aggressive.

17:44.939 --> 17:47.817
Good fighter,
not that great on a tool axe

17:47.817 --> 17:50.695
but for a thrower
or a fighter, pretty nice.

17:50.695 --> 17:52.613
It would have been nice
to see that eye

17:52.613 --> 17:55.825
be just a little bit larger
to support a larger handle.

17:55.825 --> 17:57.785
Other than that,
it looks solid.

17:57.785 --> 17:59.287
Certainly sounds solid.

17:59.287 --> 18:01.330
So very well done.

18:01.330 --> 18:03.082
- All right, JC,
you're up.

18:03.082 --> 18:05.710
Please present your hatchet
to the judges.

18:05.710 --> 18:09.922
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:09.922 --> 18:13.551
<i>- I like the overall size</i>
<i>of the eye.</i>

18:13.551 --> 18:15.428
That'll, you know,
allow for a good sized handle

18:15.428 --> 18:19.098
but with all the mass back here
and none of it up there--

18:19.098 --> 18:22.476
I mean,
you drew this down to...

18:22.476 --> 18:25.062
That's less than
an 1/8 of an inch.

18:25.062 --> 18:27.982
Which is really lean for an axe
that's going to hold up.

18:27.982 --> 18:29.984
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:29.984 --> 18:31.611
- All right, bladesmiths,

18:31.611 --> 18:33.321
only three of you
can move on to the next round

18:33.321 --> 18:35.656
so while the judges
and I go into deliberation,

18:35.656 --> 18:37.450
I'm gonna ask you to please
leave your hatchets

18:37.450 --> 18:40.119
here on the table
and step off The Forge floor.

18:40.119 --> 18:46.292
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:46.292 --> 18:48.252
- Oh.

18:48.252 --> 18:49.545
- What a day.

18:49.545 --> 18:50.963
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:50.963 --> 18:52.590
- Let's get into the details.

18:52.590 --> 18:54.884
I want to start right here
with Matt's blade.

18:54.884 --> 18:58.721
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:58.721 --> 19:01.682
- I like the classic shape
that made does over here.

19:01.682 --> 19:04.060
I'm not a big fan of, you know,
beards that come to a point

19:04.060 --> 19:05.478
'cause I want to be able
to liberate the weapon

19:05.478 --> 19:07.605
and keep using it.

19:07.605 --> 19:09.899
- His edge--
- Ah, that's the measurement

19:09.899 --> 19:12.151
I'm worried about.
- Yeah.

19:12.151 --> 19:13.653
- I think we're
all worried about

19:13.653 --> 19:15.321
that measurement right now.
- Yeah.

19:15.321 --> 19:17.865
- It's right at
4 3/4 inches that way.

19:17.865 --> 19:19.283
So he's doing fine.

19:19.283 --> 19:20.993
- Why don't we move on
to John's blade.

19:20.993 --> 19:24.413
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:24.413 --> 19:28.751
- When you put that thin body,
which is mostly mild steel,

19:28.751 --> 19:31.712
it's not hardenable,
and a very thin shaft...

19:31.712 --> 19:33.631
- Mm-hmm.
- There's a good chance

19:33.631 --> 19:35.341
that railroad tie
is gonna tear it all up.

19:35.341 --> 19:38.135
- He's got about 5 1/8th.

19:38.135 --> 19:41.013
- The issue is that
it's so thin over here.

19:41.013 --> 19:42.515
We know this is mild steel.

19:42.515 --> 19:44.100
When you use mild steel,

19:44.100 --> 19:45.559
you've got to make sure
it's thick enough

19:45.559 --> 19:47.478
to back up the hardened edge.

19:47.478 --> 19:49.689
- All right, we've got
two of our bladesmiths

19:49.689 --> 19:52.817
that pretty obviously have
missed one of our parameters.

19:52.817 --> 19:54.360
Let's talk about that.

19:54.360 --> 19:56.821
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:56.821 --> 19:59.532
So Aaron's blade is--
- 3 1/8.

19:59.532 --> 20:00.991
- Is that mine?
- That's you.

20:00.991 --> 20:02.868
- Uh-oh.

20:02.868 --> 20:04.537
Uh-oh.

20:04.537 --> 20:05.996
Yeah, I know I'm coming
under on that.

20:05.996 --> 20:07.748
3 1/8, I know--

20:07.748 --> 20:09.500
I could have swore
that's what he said though.

20:09.500 --> 20:10.918
- Aaron's got a lot
of material here.

20:10.918 --> 20:13.587
He does have meat here.

20:13.587 --> 20:15.423
He could try
to flare this out more.

20:15.423 --> 20:19.301
- All right, let's move on
to JC's blade.

20:19.301 --> 20:23.514
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:23.514 --> 20:26.475
- It is 3 1/4.
- Okay.

20:26.475 --> 20:28.519
- So neither of our smiths
hit their parameter.

20:28.519 --> 20:30.646
- Yeah, that's not--
it's not in parameters.

20:30.646 --> 20:32.690
I couldn't stretch
the beard out.

20:32.690 --> 20:37.027
<i>- JC's blade is warped</i>
<i>and paper thin.</i>

20:37.027 --> 20:38.863
<i>I mean, this is all W2</i>

20:38.863 --> 20:40.281
so it's not like
he's got mild steel

20:40.281 --> 20:41.824
he can just yank around.

20:41.824 --> 20:43.743
- Any kind of fixing
that he does with this

20:43.743 --> 20:45.703
may just make it worse.

20:45.703 --> 20:47.913
- I need you judges
to determine

20:47.913 --> 20:50.458
which of our bladesmiths
that failed to meet parameters

20:50.458 --> 20:53.961
has the better chance
of pulling it out in round two.

20:53.961 --> 20:55.337
Doug, have you made
your final decision?

20:55.337 --> 20:56.380
- Yes, I have.
- Dave?

20:56.380 --> 20:58.007
- Yeah.
- J.?

20:58.007 --> 20:59.508
- Oh, yeah.
- Let's go tell our smiths.

20:59.508 --> 21:01.635
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:01.635 --> 21:03.512
- Bladesmiths,
at the end of this round

21:03.512 --> 21:06.098
each of you was to have
turned in a hatchet head

21:06.098 --> 21:09.268
with an edge that was between
4 and 6 inches in length.

21:09.268 --> 21:11.228
Now, two of you have done that.

21:11.228 --> 21:14.607
Matt, John, you guys will be
moving on to the next round.

21:14.607 --> 21:18.110
Aaron, JC, both of your edges
came up short.

21:18.110 --> 21:19.612
The bladesmith
leaving The Forge is...

21:19.612 --> 21:23.866
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:23.866 --> 21:25.201
JC.

21:25.201 --> 21:27.244
You're blade
didn't make the cut.

21:27.244 --> 21:29.163
J. Nielson's
gonna tell you why.

21:29.163 --> 21:30.748
- At the end of the day,

21:30.748 --> 21:32.291
<i>there's not</i>
<i>enough material left</i>

21:32.291 --> 21:34.376
to be able to correct
the parameter issue

21:34.376 --> 21:36.003
and that's why
we're sending you home.

21:36.003 --> 21:38.464
- JC, please surrender
your hatchet.

21:39.673 --> 21:41.592
- I completely agree
with all the judges.

21:41.592 --> 21:44.178
<i>I didn't have enough material</i>
<i>to actually fix the mistakes</i>

21:44.178 --> 21:45.763
that they said
that I needed to fix.

21:45.763 --> 21:47.640
<i>This experience</i>
<i>has been so humbling.</i>

21:47.640 --> 21:50.017
<i>So I'm gonna go home and I'm</i>
<i>gonna rebuild a hatchet.</i>

21:50.017 --> 21:53.395
I'm going to sweat
until my shirt falls off

21:53.395 --> 21:55.231
<i>and I'm gonna come back</i>
<i>more experienced</i>

21:55.231 --> 21:56.982
<i>and with a cooler head.</i>

21:56.982 --> 21:59.360
- All right, bladesmiths,
congratulations.

21:59.360 --> 22:01.862
You're moving on to the second
round of this competition.

22:01.862 --> 22:03.864
In the second round,
you're gonna attach handles

22:03.864 --> 22:06.325
to those hatchets, turning them
into fully functional weapons.

22:06.325 --> 22:08.077
They will be tested
at the end of the round

22:08.077 --> 22:11.330
for strength and durability
in a railroad tie chop

22:11.330 --> 22:14.500
and for edge retention
in a leather bag slice.

22:14.500 --> 22:16.502
<i>Lastly, bladesmiths,</i>
<i>your hatchet handles</i>

22:16.502 --> 22:19.630
<i>must be between</i>
<i>12 and 15 inches long.</i>

22:19.630 --> 22:22.007
Aaron,
the first round parameters

22:22.007 --> 22:23.843
for that hatchet head stand.

22:23.843 --> 22:25.135
By the end
of this round,

22:25.135 --> 22:27.513
your blade must
meet parameters.

22:27.513 --> 22:29.431
And one more thing,

22:29.431 --> 22:31.016
instead of three hours
in this round,

22:31.016 --> 22:33.227
you'll get only two.

22:33.227 --> 22:36.814
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your two hours starts...now.

22:36.814 --> 22:41.902
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:41.902 --> 22:43.654
<i>- The judges said that</i>
<i>I need to address the eye.</i>

22:43.654 --> 22:45.781
<i>- John's eye is very small.</i>

22:45.781 --> 22:48.951
<i>If I were him, I'd heat it</i>
<i>back up and widen it out.</i>

22:48.951 --> 22:50.911
- My plan,
as of right now,

22:50.911 --> 22:53.622
<i>is just cut that hatchet eye</i>
<i>completely off.</i>

22:53.622 --> 22:54.999
There's pipe
that I'm gonna use.

22:54.999 --> 22:56.876
It'll make a perfect axe eye.

22:56.876 --> 22:58.627
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:58.627 --> 22:59.962
- Ha!

22:59.962 --> 23:01.881
John's gonna cut
his stock off

23:01.881 --> 23:03.299
and weld on a piece of pipe.

23:03.299 --> 23:05.843
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:05.843 --> 23:08.304
That's brilliant.

23:08.304 --> 23:10.598
- You know, this would really,
really worry me

23:10.598 --> 23:12.975
if he wasn't a pipe cutter.
- Yeah, if--

23:12.975 --> 23:14.476
- I'm sure he can weld
the crap out of that.

23:14.476 --> 23:17.062
- Oh, that's just it,
this man's a welder.

23:17.062 --> 23:19.189
Oh, I love
great work arounds.

23:19.189 --> 23:20.733
[laughs]

23:20.733 --> 23:22.693
- That's at 3.

23:22.693 --> 23:25.237
Let's bring it out to 4.

23:25.237 --> 23:28.824
- Aaron has to come up
with some creative way

23:28.824 --> 23:32.202
to add almost an inch of length
to his hatchet's edge.

23:32.202 --> 23:34.204
<i>- With me being</i>
<i>under parameters,</i>

23:34.204 --> 23:36.540
<i>I was extremely close</i>
<i>to going home.</i>

23:36.540 --> 23:39.084
I could have swore he said,
"3 inches being the minimum."

23:39.084 --> 23:41.086
I guess I was wrong.

23:41.086 --> 23:44.340
<i>If I don't meet the parameters</i>
<i>within the second round</i>

23:44.340 --> 23:45.674
that's gonna be a case
for me to go home.

23:45.674 --> 23:48.802
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:48.802 --> 23:51.263
- Aaron has added
about a 1x1 square

23:51.263 --> 23:52.848
to the bottom
of his blade.

23:52.848 --> 23:54.558
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:54.558 --> 23:56.101
I just hope it stays on.

23:56.101 --> 23:58.395
I'm gonna hit
that whole thing.

23:58.395 --> 24:00.981
<i>- So when they told us</i>
<i>it was two hours I was like,</i>

24:00.981 --> 24:03.442
"Ugh, well, maybe..."

24:03.442 --> 24:05.444
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:05.444 --> 24:09.657
<i>I have to fix the misalignment</i>
<i>of the socket.</i>

24:09.657 --> 24:11.784
I want to heat it up,
I want to straighten that out,

24:11.784 --> 24:13.744
<i>and get it nice and lined up</i>
<i>with the handle.</i>

24:13.744 --> 24:15.788
So I run over
and grab the drift.

24:15.788 --> 24:17.373
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:17.373 --> 24:19.124
<i>I can torque it around</i>

24:19.124 --> 24:21.752
<i>and it will hold</i>
<i>that interior shape.</i>

24:21.752 --> 24:24.213
Whoo!

24:24.213 --> 24:27.675
- Bladesmiths,
half an hour has elapsed.

24:27.675 --> 24:30.928
You have just 90 minutes
remaining to finish your work.

24:30.928 --> 24:33.514
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:33.514 --> 24:36.892
- Look down the side
of John's hatchet face

24:36.892 --> 24:39.478
and you're gonna see all
of these, like, welded lines.

24:39.478 --> 24:40.896
What's the point of that, J.?

24:40.896 --> 24:43.941
- Just reinforcing
that thin body.

24:43.941 --> 24:45.859
<i>- A lot of people</i>
<i>think that welding,</i>

24:45.859 --> 24:49.530
you just put metals
on the surface of the steel

24:49.530 --> 24:52.074
<i>you're actually getting down</i>
<i>into whatever you're welding.</i>

24:52.074 --> 24:54.159
<i>Reheating steel like that</i>

24:54.159 --> 24:56.161
is definitely gonna
take my hardness out.

24:56.161 --> 25:00.040
- John has to re-temper,
re-quench his blade.

25:00.040 --> 25:03.210
<i>- When you quench, you never</i>
<i>know what could happen.</i>

25:03.210 --> 25:05.087
It could just all pop loose.

25:05.087 --> 25:11.760
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:13.971 --> 25:16.640
- Sounds good.
- It's singing.

25:16.640 --> 25:19.935
<i>- I'm super excited</i>
<i>that I've fixes those issues.</i>

25:19.935 --> 25:21.603
I think it's gonna
turn out really good.

25:21.603 --> 25:24.106
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:24.106 --> 25:26.316
- I'm clearly behind.

25:26.316 --> 25:29.028
That's why I gotta go
for the friction fit handle.

25:29.028 --> 25:31.280
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:31.280 --> 25:33.323
It's quick, dirty, and easy.

25:33.323 --> 25:35.159
<i>But with a locking pin</i>

25:35.159 --> 25:37.036
it will prevent the head
from coming off of the handle,

25:37.036 --> 25:38.829
which is definitely
what you want.

25:38.829 --> 25:40.873
Not looking bad at all.

25:40.873 --> 25:43.917
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:43.917 --> 25:46.295
- Not the best way
to put a handle on.

25:46.295 --> 25:47.838
- That's bad physics.
- Yes.

25:47.838 --> 25:49.840
- [laughs]
- Yes.

25:49.840 --> 25:53.052
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:53.052 --> 25:55.179
<i>- When I was hammering</i>
<i>the axe head on,</i>

25:55.179 --> 25:58.849
I got some splintering at
the handle down at the bottom.

25:58.849 --> 26:00.350
- There we go.
- Uh-oh.

26:00.350 --> 26:02.269
- Hope it didn't break--
crack his wood.

26:02.269 --> 26:03.979
- How can I fix this?

26:03.979 --> 26:06.482
<i>I don't have time</i>
<i>to start over again.</i>

26:06.482 --> 26:08.609
I don't want a piece
of my handle to come off

26:08.609 --> 26:10.235
because that's grounds
for saying, you're out of here.

26:12.802 --> 26:14.738
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:14.738 --> 26:17.449
And then I remember,
glue could fix this.

26:17.449 --> 26:21.286
- Matt is gluing
the butt end of his handle.

26:21.286 --> 26:24.205
- Filled it full of five-minute
epoxy, wrapped it with tape.

26:24.205 --> 26:25.915
It's not an area
that's gonna take shock

26:25.915 --> 26:27.459
unless Doug decides to,

26:27.459 --> 26:29.461
you know,
butt somebody with it.

26:29.461 --> 26:32.213
So I think I'm good, but...

26:32.213 --> 26:34.049
- 30 minutes, bladesmiths.

26:34.049 --> 26:36.009
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:36.009 --> 26:38.762
- I realize I need
to pick it up.

26:38.762 --> 26:41.097
Right now it's a little loose
but I'm making me some wedges.

26:41.097 --> 26:42.557
I'm gonna wedge it out.

26:42.557 --> 26:47.812
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:47.812 --> 26:50.065
- Every time he puts in
one of those wedges,

26:50.065 --> 26:52.609
underneath the head,
there's a crack forming.

26:52.609 --> 26:54.235
- Ugh.

26:54.235 --> 26:57.364
- This could be
devastating for John.

26:57.364 --> 27:00.158
<i>- I don't want that crack to</i>
<i>go any further down the handle</i>

27:00.158 --> 27:02.202
<i>so I put leather on it.</i>

27:02.202 --> 27:04.412
- John's basically putting
a bandage on his handle.

27:04.412 --> 27:05.664
- A big leather band-aid.

27:05.664 --> 27:08.583
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:08.583 --> 27:10.543
<i>- Performance is</i>
<i>what matters here.</i>

27:10.543 --> 27:13.171
It can't be too sharp.

27:13.171 --> 27:17.133
<i>So I start shaving my arm</i>
<i>and I also get some paper</i>

27:17.133 --> 27:21.221
<i>to make sure the cuts</i>
<i>are nice and clean.</i>

27:21.221 --> 27:23.264
Then I decide,
well, let's test it

27:23.264 --> 27:25.100
a little more
realistically.

27:25.100 --> 27:27.727
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:27.727 --> 27:29.020
I'm totally pumped.

27:29.020 --> 27:31.064
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:31.064 --> 27:33.024
- If Aaron wants to get that
pin in, he better hurry up.

27:33.024 --> 27:35.360
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:35.360 --> 27:36.861
- Oh, man, Aaron.
- Oh.

27:36.861 --> 27:38.905
- Oh my God, the pin
isn't going in for Aaron.

27:38.905 --> 27:42.117
<i>- It's a bold choice</i>
<i>to put the locking pin</i>

27:42.117 --> 27:44.494
into the head of the hatchet

27:44.494 --> 27:46.204
but it's definitely
a crucial thing.

27:46.204 --> 27:48.373
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:50.041 --> 27:52.585
<i>- So putting some gloves</i>
<i>underneath the hatchet</i>

27:52.585 --> 27:54.921
raised it up just enough that
way that side could be peened

27:54.921 --> 27:56.256
while I'm peening the top end.

27:56.256 --> 27:57.882
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

27:57.882 --> 28:00.760
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.

28:00.760 --> 28:02.387
- Hey, you gotta do
what you gotta do.

28:02.387 --> 28:05.557
- Five, four, three,

28:05.557 --> 28:07.559
two, one...

28:07.559 --> 28:10.270
Bladesmiths, drop your tools
and shut down your machines.

28:10.270 --> 28:13.064
This round is over.

28:13.064 --> 28:15.275
<i>- Very confident</i>
<i>that I've hit parameters.</i>

28:15.275 --> 28:17.610
This time I think
my confidence is true.

28:17.610 --> 28:19.446
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

28:19.446 --> 28:21.823
- [laughs]
Welcome, smiths.

28:21.823 --> 28:23.199
You know why I'm here.

28:23.199 --> 28:25.160
We're gonna do
the strength test now.

28:25.160 --> 28:27.162
Now I'm gonna take
each of your hatchets

28:27.162 --> 28:29.914
and I'm gonna strike
this railroad tie...

28:29.914 --> 28:32.375
repeatedly and violently.

28:32.375 --> 28:33.710
We're gonna see,
not what your hatchets

28:33.710 --> 28:35.295
do to the railroad tie,

28:35.295 --> 28:37.255
but what the railroad tie
does to your hatchets.

28:37.255 --> 28:38.756
Matt, you're up first.
Are you ready?

28:38.756 --> 28:41.009
- No.
- Well, I'm gonna do it anyway.

28:41.009 --> 28:42.427
<i>- This is it.</i>

28:42.427 --> 28:44.387
<i>J.'s got a look in his eye</i>

28:44.387 --> 28:46.556
<i>like he's gonna beat the crap</i>
<i>out of that timber.</i>

28:46.556 --> 28:48.725
So I'm just--I'm really worried
it's gonna come apart.

28:48.725 --> 28:52.353
<i>[intense music]</i>

28:52.353 --> 28:55.273
- [grunting]

28:55.273 --> 29:02.197
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:06.326 --> 29:07.577
- [sighs]
- There you go.

29:07.577 --> 29:09.078
- [laughs]

29:09.078 --> 29:10.580
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:10.580 --> 29:12.415
- Nicely done, Matt.
Your edge is fine.

29:12.415 --> 29:13.666
No damage.

29:13.666 --> 29:15.126
You're slightly out
of alignment

29:15.126 --> 29:17.587
with your edge here,
but it's slight,

29:17.587 --> 29:19.506
so I was able
to correct easily.

29:19.506 --> 29:21.466
Everything's tight.
Nothing moved.

29:21.466 --> 29:23.384
The handle's just a little big

29:23.384 --> 29:24.844
but I like having it
flare on the bottom.

29:24.844 --> 29:26.346
You did a great job.
Congratulations.

29:26.346 --> 29:27.805
- Thank you.

29:27.805 --> 29:30.099
- John,
we're gonna do you next.

29:30.099 --> 29:32.727
<i>- J. said he's gonna violently</i>
<i>strike this railroad tie.</i>

29:32.727 --> 29:35.188
<i>He has his violent.</i>
<i>I have my violent.</i>

29:35.188 --> 29:37.649
I like to give hugs and kisses
for my violent.

29:37.649 --> 29:39.484
<i>We would just have to see</i>
<i>what he does.</i>

29:39.484 --> 29:41.778
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:41.778 --> 29:44.781
- [grunting]

29:44.781 --> 29:51.663
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:53.498 --> 29:54.624
- [exhales]

29:54.624 --> 29:59.045
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:59.045 --> 30:00.296
- Nice job, John.

30:00.296 --> 30:01.839
Everything's still tight.

30:01.839 --> 30:03.424
So the leather band-aid

30:03.424 --> 30:04.592
worked very well
to hold things together.

30:04.592 --> 30:06.719
You did do
a rough index down here

30:06.719 --> 30:08.429
but it feels almost triangular,

30:08.429 --> 30:10.431
so it's a little odd
but it worked well.

30:10.431 --> 30:11.891
Good job.

30:11.891 --> 30:13.726
Aaron, you're up next.
You ready?

30:13.726 --> 30:15.770
- Fire away, sir.

30:15.770 --> 30:19.649
<i>All I have is just sheer hope</i>
<i>that this is gonna last.</i>

30:19.649 --> 30:22.193
Hopefully,
it's not gonna tear off

30:22.193 --> 30:23.820
or break welds
or anything like that.

30:23.820 --> 30:25.196
So fingers crossed, for sure.

30:25.196 --> 30:32.203
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:35.331 --> 30:37.000
- There's a problem here.

30:37.000 --> 30:38.315
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:41.674 --> 30:42.633
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:42.633 --> 30:48.264
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:51.309 --> 30:59.293
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:01.045 --> 31:03.422
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:03.422 --> 31:04.757
- Gentlemen,
there was a minimum

31:04.757 --> 31:06.258
and maximum length parameter

31:06.258 --> 31:08.219
for the handles
of your hatchets.

31:08.219 --> 31:12.515
Your hatchet handle is over
by 3/4 of an inch.

31:12.515 --> 31:14.183
You now have
the dubious distinction

31:14.183 --> 31:15.893
of being the only bladesmith

31:15.893 --> 31:17.770
that's ever participated
on this show

31:17.770 --> 31:19.814
to blow the parameters
both rounds.

31:19.814 --> 31:21.357
That's a little bit
disappointing from somebody

31:21.357 --> 31:22.942
who has so much talent.

31:22.942 --> 31:25.236
So, at this time,
I have to ask you,

31:25.236 --> 31:26.529
please leave The Forge, Aaron.

31:26.529 --> 31:27.822
- Yes, sir.
- Sorry, man.

31:27.822 --> 31:29.114
That sucks, I'm sorry.

31:29.114 --> 31:30.950
<i>- I'm a little bummed out.</i>

31:30.950 --> 31:32.493
I should have been a little
bit more patient with it

31:32.493 --> 31:34.578
and a little more diligent
about noticing

31:34.578 --> 31:36.539
<i>the parameters of what I had.</i>

31:36.539 --> 31:38.874
What I've learned
from this experience is...

31:38.874 --> 31:41.252
<i>measure twice, cut once.</i>

31:41.252 --> 31:42.795
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:42.795 --> 31:44.338
- Matt, John, congratulations.

31:44.338 --> 31:45.673
You two have made it
to the final round

31:45.673 --> 31:47.591
of this competition,

31:47.591 --> 31:50.761
which means your closer
to that check for $10,000

31:50.761 --> 31:52.513
and the title
of "Forged in Fire" champion,

31:52.513 --> 31:54.431
but you're not quite there yet.

31:54.431 --> 31:56.475
You still have to go home
and recreate

31:56.475 --> 31:58.185
an iconic weapon from history.

31:58.185 --> 31:59.728
Are you ready to see
what that weapon is?

31:59.728 --> 32:02.189
- Sure.
- All right, that weapon is...

32:02.189 --> 32:04.608
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:04.608 --> 32:07.027
That is a Maasai Lion's Spear.

32:07.027 --> 32:08.696
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:08.696 --> 32:10.614
<i>The Maasai Lion's Spear</i>
<i>gets its name</i>

32:10.614 --> 32:13.534
<i>from an east African tribe</i>
<i>of fearsome warrior nomads</i>

32:13.534 --> 32:16.161
<i>that date their origins</i>
<i>back to the 15th century.</i>

32:16.161 --> 32:18.247
<i>Traditionally used</i>
<i>to hunt lions,</i>

32:18.247 --> 32:20.958
<i>the weapon features a</i>
<i>double-edged blade at one end</i>

32:20.958 --> 32:23.002
<i>and a fearsome spike</i>
<i>at the other.</i>

32:23.002 --> 32:25.504
<i>This allows a Maasai warrior</i>
<i>to engage his opponent</i>

32:25.504 --> 32:27.298
<i>in close quarters</i>
<i>or at a distance.</i>

32:27.298 --> 32:29.300
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:29.300 --> 32:31.176
<i>While, today,</i>
<i>lion hunts have been replaced,</i>

32:31.176 --> 32:33.762
<i>the deadly spear lives on</i>
<i>in popular culture</i>

32:33.762 --> 32:35.681
<i>and can even be spotted</i>
<i>in the film</i>

32:35.681 --> 32:38.601
<i>"Lara Croft: Tomb Raider -</i>
<i>The Cradle of Life."</i>

32:38.601 --> 32:41.103
Your job is to recreate

32:41.103 --> 32:44.440
a functional and working
version of this blade.

32:44.440 --> 32:47.318
However, we want you
to put your own spin on it

32:47.318 --> 32:49.570
as long as
your spear falls

32:49.570 --> 32:51.488
within the following
parameters:

32:51.488 --> 32:53.407
On the flared end,
you must have a blade

32:53.407 --> 32:56.201
that is between
23 and 25 inches in length.

32:56.201 --> 32:58.370
On the opposite end
of your spear,

32:58.370 --> 33:00.039
your piercing
and puncturing end,

33:00.039 --> 33:01.665
you must again have a blade

33:01.665 --> 33:04.835
that's between
23 and 25 inches in length

33:04.835 --> 33:06.962
and the sockets
on both of your spear heads

33:06.962 --> 33:09.715
must fall between
8 and 10 inches in length.

33:09.715 --> 33:11.091
You'll have five days
at your home forge

33:11.091 --> 33:12.718
to complete this challenge.

33:12.718 --> 33:14.511
At the end of five days
you will return

33:14.511 --> 33:16.722
and present
your Maasai Lion's Spears

33:16.722 --> 33:18.724
to our panel of expert Judges.

33:18.724 --> 33:21.685
Only after they've tested them
and examined your work,

33:21.685 --> 33:24.563
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

33:24.563 --> 33:27.691
who also walks out of here
with a check for $10,000.

33:27.691 --> 33:31.111
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in five days.

33:31.111 --> 33:32.446
- Good luck, John.

33:32.446 --> 33:35.574
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:35.574 --> 33:37.368
<i>- I'm back</i>
<i>in Corsicana, Texas,</i>

33:37.368 --> 33:40.245
<i>and I'm super excited</i>
<i>to start this project.</i>

33:40.245 --> 33:42.498
The biggest challenge for today
is trying to get

33:42.498 --> 33:45.584
the spike end of the spear
forged out

33:45.584 --> 33:47.878
and the socket forged out
and have it all in one piece.

33:47.878 --> 33:49.755
<i>I'm gonna try</i>
<i>and, you know,</i>

33:49.755 --> 33:51.090
take it slow
and steady today.

33:51.090 --> 33:52.549
<i>[folksy music]</i>

33:52.549 --> 33:54.343
You want those?

33:54.343 --> 33:56.345
The mornings with my daughter
are just the best.

33:56.345 --> 33:58.931
Daddy's dizzy.

33:58.931 --> 34:00.516
So I'm playing
with my baby girl

34:00.516 --> 34:02.184
<i>and I realize that</i>
<i>I left the socket</i>

34:02.184 --> 34:04.478
in the forge too long.

34:04.478 --> 34:07.189
It got hot and it just
fell to the ground, melted.

34:07.189 --> 34:08.857
<i>My whole socket's gone.</i>

34:08.857 --> 34:11.735
<i>I've just wasted</i>
<i>this huge amount of time.</i>

34:11.735 --> 34:14.113
Right now I'm just gonna forget
about this whole socket deal

34:14.113 --> 34:17.032
<i>and I'm gonna grab this rebar</i>
<i>and start forging the spike.</i>

34:17.032 --> 34:20.035
I didn't get as much
accomplished as I wanted to.

34:20.035 --> 34:22.538
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:22.538 --> 34:25.082
<i>- I'm very happy to be back</i>
<i>in my workshop.</i>

34:25.082 --> 34:27.084
<i>My day one game plan is</i>

34:27.084 --> 34:30.254
<i>start forging</i>
<i>the slashing blade.</i>

34:30.254 --> 34:33.674
<i>I haven't really made</i>
<i>anything like this before.</i>

34:33.674 --> 34:36.802
<i>I got the blade</i>
<i>completely forged</i>

34:36.802 --> 34:40.764
and I think it is now time
to finish the socket.

34:40.764 --> 34:43.600
<i>I've got</i>
<i>the start of the socket</i>

34:43.600 --> 34:45.811
<i>and so now I need</i>
<i>to start flaring it.</i>

34:45.811 --> 34:48.439
<i>I'm hitting it a lot</i>
<i>and it's just not moving much.</i>

34:48.439 --> 34:51.817
So I decided I needed
to try something different.

34:51.817 --> 34:54.695
This is called
a Portuguese stake.

34:54.695 --> 34:57.406
All right, let's see
what this can do for me.

34:57.406 --> 35:00.534
So I try flaring it with that
and it flared.

35:00.534 --> 35:01.702
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:01.702 --> 35:04.371
You can come off.

35:04.371 --> 35:06.040
As it's cooling
it's gonna shrink

35:06.040 --> 35:08.083
<i>so now I'm</i>
<i>a little panicked about this.</i>

35:08.083 --> 35:09.960
<i>If I can't</i>
<i>get this off, well,</i>

35:09.960 --> 35:12.463
I've lost at least
two hours work right there.

35:12.463 --> 35:14.048
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:14.048 --> 35:15.674
Tool for every occasion.

35:15.674 --> 35:17.301
I am ready for bed.

35:17.301 --> 35:19.595
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:19.595 --> 35:22.014
- It's hot out here.
- [cooing]

35:22.014 --> 35:24.391
<i>- The biggest obstacle today</i>
<i>is gonna be the heat treat.</i>

35:24.391 --> 35:27.061
<i>I wanna make sure that the</i>
<i>blade is good and straight.</i>

35:27.061 --> 35:29.271
<i>If this heat treat goes</i>
<i>the way I think it's gonna go,</i>

35:29.271 --> 35:32.566
<i>I'm gonna be sitting</i>
<i>very well, time-wise.</i>

35:32.566 --> 35:34.109
Turn and burn, baby.
Let's go.

35:34.109 --> 35:35.277
<i>Let's move fast.</i>

35:35.277 --> 35:36.987
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:36.987 --> 35:38.739
<i>If it does get</i>
<i>a significant warp,</i>

35:38.739 --> 35:41.367
<i>I really don't know</i>
<i>what to do.</i>

35:41.367 --> 35:43.118
Ah, [bleep].

35:43.118 --> 35:45.329
It looks like it's got
a real sharp curve to it.

35:45.329 --> 35:47.581
It's just--it's bad.

35:47.581 --> 35:49.750
<i>Really, I was speechless.</i>
<i>I didn't know what to do.</i>

35:49.750 --> 35:51.919
<i>I might have to start</i>
<i>a whole 'nother piece.</i>

35:55.464 --> 35:57.299
<i>♪ ♪</i>
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:57.299 --> 35:59.468
<i>- I might have to start</i>
<i>a whole 'nother piece.</i>

35:59.468 --> 36:01.178
I don't know.

36:01.178 --> 36:03.680
I realize that,
let's just end it here.

36:03.680 --> 36:05.391
Let's start anew.

36:05.391 --> 36:09.228
So I light the propane forge
and start over.

36:09.228 --> 36:11.772
That's some big ol' stuff
right there now.

36:11.772 --> 36:13.732
I probably lost
about a whole day

36:13.732 --> 36:15.776
<i>on this blade portion.</i>

36:15.776 --> 36:18.904
I am wore smooth out.

36:18.904 --> 36:22.658
<i>- So I finished the heat treat</i>
<i>on the slashing blade</i>

36:22.658 --> 36:24.326
<i>and it came out great,</i>

36:24.326 --> 36:25.702
so I'm gonna get to work
on the handle.

36:25.702 --> 36:27.704
<i>I'm gonna use ash</i>
<i>for the handle.</i>

36:27.704 --> 36:30.416
<i>That's what they make</i>
<i>most baseball bats out of.</i>

36:30.416 --> 36:32.459
<i>So if the handle is</i>
<i>gonna break anywhere,</i>

36:32.459 --> 36:34.336
it's gonna break right at
the base of the socket

36:34.336 --> 36:36.338
where they connect,

36:36.338 --> 36:38.257
<i>but I think it's thick enough</i>
<i>that it's gonna hold up.</i>

36:38.257 --> 36:39.967
I just don't see
that being a problem.

36:39.967 --> 36:43.262
<i>I test fit the spike</i>
<i>and the blade on...</i>

36:43.262 --> 36:45.931
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:45.931 --> 36:48.892
[mimics crying]
My blade's crooked.

36:48.892 --> 36:50.436
I gotta do something
about this,

36:50.436 --> 36:52.396
I can't send this
down to the judges.

36:52.396 --> 36:55.065
Ooh, ooh.
No, I know.

36:55.065 --> 36:59.153
I realized that
all I have to do is

36:59.153 --> 37:02.823
rotate the spearhead
180 degrees.

37:02.823 --> 37:04.408
Hey!
Much better.

37:04.408 --> 37:06.326
Perfect!
[laughs]

37:06.326 --> 37:09.288
So crisis is averted.
I'm psyched.

37:09.288 --> 37:10.664
It looks like this
is gonna go together

37:10.664 --> 37:12.624
and be really sweet.

37:12.624 --> 37:14.751
<i>- I've got a really long day</i>
<i>ahead of me.</i>

37:14.751 --> 37:16.003
<i>Gotta get a lot</i>
<i>of things done.</i>

37:16.003 --> 37:17.713
<i>Had a little setback yesterday</i>

37:17.713 --> 37:19.673
<i>but today I've just</i>
<i>gotta repeat yesterday.</i>

37:19.673 --> 37:21.967
I'm trying to do
a lot of things at once.

37:21.967 --> 37:23.719
<i>I've got a 25 inch handle</i>
<i>that I need to make.</i>

37:23.719 --> 37:25.429
[laughs]

37:25.429 --> 37:26.972
<i>I'm gonna get</i>
<i>everything normalized.</i>

37:26.972 --> 37:28.765
<i>If the blade warps,</i>

37:28.765 --> 37:30.434
<i>hopefully I've got</i>
<i>enough material to fix it.</i>

37:30.434 --> 37:31.935
<i>And I'm gonna</i>
<i>make this thing work,</i>

37:31.935 --> 37:32.978
<i>come hell or high water.</i>

37:32.978 --> 37:34.605
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:34.605 --> 37:36.106
Ah, dadgummit.

37:36.106 --> 37:38.484
It snaps.
I just--I'm shocked.

37:38.484 --> 37:40.068
<i>I don't--I'm speechless.</i>

37:40.068 --> 37:43.030
<i>I just don't know</i>
<i>what to do.</i>

37:43.030 --> 37:45.782
I'm bummed.
I am bummed, bummed, bummed.

37:45.782 --> 37:47.826
So I've got two main options.

37:47.826 --> 37:51.914
<i>One option would be</i>
<i>to go back to the first blade.</i>

37:51.914 --> 37:54.416
I think I'm gonna--
to go with another option

37:54.416 --> 37:56.084
<i>and that's to TIG weld it.</i>

37:56.084 --> 37:57.794
I'm just gonna have
to push through this.

37:57.794 --> 38:00.255
- It's day five. Whoo-hoo!
[laughs]

38:00.255 --> 38:02.758
<i>Spears glued together</i>
<i>over night.</i>

38:02.758 --> 38:03.967
I'm gonna work on the pins
to make sure

38:03.967 --> 38:05.594
the sockets don't come off.

38:05.594 --> 38:07.971
<i>I start working</i>
<i>on the spike end</i>

38:07.971 --> 38:09.681
<i>and I'm tapping the pin in</i>
<i>and something's wrong,</i>

38:09.681 --> 38:11.350
<i>it's not going in</i>
<i>like it should.</i>

38:11.350 --> 38:13.185
[grunts]

38:13.185 --> 38:16.438
Another day
of things getting stuck.

38:16.438 --> 38:18.732
[grunts]
Oh.

38:18.732 --> 38:20.317
[groans]

38:20.317 --> 38:21.652
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:21.652 --> 38:23.153
[sighs]

38:23.153 --> 38:25.948
So the spear has drawn
its first blood.

38:25.948 --> 38:28.992
<i>[tense music]</i>

38:28.992 --> 38:31.620
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:31.620 --> 38:33.330
- Matt, John,
welcome back to The Forge.

38:33.330 --> 38:35.374
You've had five days
at your home forges

38:35.374 --> 38:38.752
to work on your finale spears.
Matt, how did it go?

38:38.752 --> 38:40.671
- I managed to punch myself
in the face

38:40.671 --> 38:42.881
with some locking pliers, but
other than that it was good.

38:42.881 --> 38:44.508
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:44.508 --> 38:47.553
<i>The sockets are mild steel</i>

38:47.553 --> 38:51.723
<i>that are forge welded onto</i>
<i>a 1075 blade and spike.</i>

38:51.723 --> 38:53.517
- John, how'd it go for you?

38:53.517 --> 38:55.352
- I pulled some magic
out of a hat

38:55.352 --> 38:58.480
and made some
crazy things happen.

38:58.480 --> 39:00.899
<i>I made the sockets</i>
<i>out of stainless steel.</i>

39:00.899 --> 39:03.026
<i>The blade is 5160</i>

39:03.026 --> 39:05.279
<i>and the spike is</i>
<i>a piece of rebar.</i>

39:05.279 --> 39:07.489
- All right, gentlemen,
there will be a strength test,

39:07.489 --> 39:09.116
a sharpness test, and up first,

39:09.116 --> 39:11.034
the kill test.
Doug.

39:11.034 --> 39:13.620
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:13.620 --> 39:15.664
- To see how lethal
your weapon is,

39:15.664 --> 39:17.666
I will take your spear
and deliver lethal blows

39:17.666 --> 39:19.543
on this pig carcass.

39:19.543 --> 39:21.587
Matt, you're up first.
Are you ready?

39:21.587 --> 39:23.589
- Ready as I'll ever be.
- Let's do this.

39:23.589 --> 39:26.049
<i>- What I'm most worried about</i>

39:26.049 --> 39:28.135
<i>is lateral force</i>
<i>on this spear</i>

39:28.135 --> 39:30.971
because it's a very thin,
sleek spear.

39:30.971 --> 39:37.894
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:40.063 --> 39:43.761
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:49.648 --> 39:56.571
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:02.577 --> 40:04.037
[tings]

40:04.037 --> 40:05.580
[clangs]

40:05.580 --> 40:12.504
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:14.798 --> 40:16.549
- Well...

40:16.549 --> 40:18.259
that sucks.
[chuckles]

40:18.259 --> 40:25.100
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:28.019 --> 40:29.938
- Matt, I'm not gonna
sugar coat it.

40:29.938 --> 40:31.648
This is bad.

40:31.648 --> 40:34.067
Your weapon has suffered
a catastrophic failure

40:34.067 --> 40:36.236
and cannot continue
with testing, however...

40:36.236 --> 40:38.947
John, we can't just declare you
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

40:38.947 --> 40:40.657
your blade has to hold up

40:40.657 --> 40:43.743
for a least a stab
and a slash on this carcass.

40:43.743 --> 40:45.328
Doug.

40:45.328 --> 40:48.540
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:48.540 --> 40:51.084
<i>- I don't know what to say.</i>
<i>I don't know what to think.</i>

40:51.084 --> 40:54.921
<i>I've never been more,</i>
<i>you know, nervous in my life.</i>

40:54.921 --> 40:56.423
I'm hoping and praying that

40:56.423 --> 40:57.799
it doesn't break
in the same spot.

40:57.799 --> 41:04.639
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:10.770 --> 41:17.527
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:19.946 --> 41:23.158
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:23.158 --> 41:24.659
- Bladesmiths,
as they're designed,

41:24.659 --> 41:27.245
these tests push your weapons
to the limit.

41:27.245 --> 41:31.332
John, your blade survived
the two cuts on our carcass.

41:31.332 --> 41:33.710
Matt, that means,
unfortunately,

41:33.710 --> 41:35.795
your blade did not
make the cut.

41:35.795 --> 41:38.339
I'm gonna have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

41:38.339 --> 41:40.050
- Congrats, man.
I'm happy for you.

41:40.050 --> 41:42.052
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:42.052 --> 41:43.887
I'm disappointed.

41:43.887 --> 41:46.181
<i>Given what I know now,</i>
<i>I would have gone back</i>

41:46.181 --> 41:49.184
and really tried chopping some
things very hard with the spear

41:49.184 --> 41:51.186
and hopefully
broken the handle myself.

41:51.186 --> 41:52.937
<i>I'm really happy for John.</i>

41:52.937 --> 41:54.606
Maybe I'm not happy
to lose to John,

41:54.606 --> 41:57.275
but I'm glad John won.

41:57.275 --> 41:58.735
- John, congratulations.

41:58.735 --> 42:00.445
You built a weapon
that held up in our test.

42:00.445 --> 42:02.322
That makes you our
new "Forged in Fire" champion

42:02.322 --> 42:04.574
who also receives
a check for ten grand.

42:04.574 --> 42:07.577
[applause]

42:07.577 --> 42:09.704
How do you feel right now?

42:09.704 --> 42:11.915
- I feel like a million bucks
but I guess ten grand will do.

42:11.915 --> 42:13.583
- [laughs]
All right.

42:13.583 --> 42:15.210
Well, come on over here
and shake our hands.

42:15.210 --> 42:16.336
- Good job, bud.
- Thank you.

42:16.336 --> 42:17.754
- Very good.

42:17.754 --> 42:19.422
- I'm gonna have to talk
to my wife about

42:19.422 --> 42:22.258
what I'm allowed to do
with this prize money.

42:22.258 --> 42:24.052
<i>I know one thing,</i>
<i>my baby girl's gonna--</i>

42:24.052 --> 42:25.887
getting a little new wardrobe.

42:25.887 --> 42:26.805
<i>♪ ♪</i>
